{
  "texts": [
    "We will prove this by showing that the measure of the set",
    "Since the rightmost hand side goes to zero as m → ∞, we have µ(E(N, ℓ)) = 0.",
    "Suppose that ℓ = 2.",
    "We use [Jar75, Lemma 5.1] with e = 1, θ = 1/3.",
    "Then we have µ(E(N, 2, m)) ≤ µ(E(2 (m-1)/3, 2, m)) ≤ c 2 m/3, where the first inequality holds for all m ≥ 3 log N/ log 2 + 1 and c is a positive constant independent of m. Taking m → ∞ leads us to conclude that µ(E(N, 2)) = 0."
  ]
}